\section*{1. Binding, fusion and entry}
- During this step, viral gp120 binds to the CD4 receptor and CCR5 or CXCR4 co-receptor on the host surface
- The binding facilitates the fusion of viral and host cell membrane thereby facilitating the entry of viral nuclear material into the host cell

\section*{2. Reverse transcription}
- Viral RNA is reverse transcribed to viral DNA
- This process is mediated by the enzyme reverse transcriptase (RT)
- This enzyme has no proof-reading function, and therefore the process is error-prone and responsible for development of drug-resistant mutations

\section*{3. Integration}
- The viral DNA is inserted into host cell DNA using the viral enzyme integrase
- This is the process that establishes replication-competent virus in the body and makes HIV incurable even with effective ART
- Further, drug-resistant virus that occurs in patients on ART may also be achieved in the same way, establishing a permanent pool of resistant viruses.

\section*{4. Transcription and Translation}
- Host cell enzymes transcribe viral DNA into viral RNA
- Viral RNA uses host cell energy and synthetic pathways to make viral proteins

\section*{5. Assembly, budding and maturation}
- Viral proteins and RNA aggregate on the cell surface for assembly into a mature viral particle by budding through host cell membrane

